# The Book of Motion

A book about **how things move**. Not the sprites that move — that is
Marionette. Not the pictures that get drawn as they move — that is
Animation. This book is about the physics-of-feel underneath: position
in time, the shape of an arc, the weight of a thing that falls, the
way a thing settles when it stops, the way a thing trails when it is
pulled.

Motion in Motoi Scheme is not a bag of per-material verbs. There is
no `brick/fall` and no `feather/drift`. There is one small set of
general primitives, and everything material-specific is a **parameter
regime** over those primitives — the gravity you set, the settle
easing you pick, the squash you allow, the lag you let the secondary
motion take. A brick and a petal are the same code with different
numbers.

*When I move something, I am not casting a spell called \"make this
feel heavy.\" I am picking a set of numbers. High gravity, short
bounce, brief squash, no drift. That is heavy. Low gravity, long
elastic settle, big slow lag, some drift. That is floaty. The verbs
are the same. What changes is who I am pretending the thing is.*

Every fenced program in this book is a full runnable program. Not one
of them is a fragment. If you paste any block into `motoi-scheme
repl`, it runs through the sealed interpreter and prints something you
can compare against. That is what \"living tutorial\" means: the claims
verify themselves.

## The first five chapters

1. [[#chapter-1]] **What motion is.** Position, velocity, and the
   step. The three numbers a moving thing has and how they change
   when the world takes a step.
2. [[#chapter-2]] **The embodiment axis.** Brick-heavy to petal-floaty
   on one dial. The `:embodiment` parameter regime and how to read a
   felt adjective off it.
3. [[#chapter-3]] **Easing and overshoot.** Cubic-bezier easings and
   spring physics side by side. When each one is right, and how a
   little overshoot is the difference between a stiff arrival and a
   living one.
4. [[#chapter-4]] **Settling and lag.** How a thing comes to rest.
   How a thing that follows another thing trails behind. Secondary
   motion — the tail on the kite.
5. [[#chapter-5]] **Composing motion.** Stacking motion primitives on
   the same sprite. When composition adds up cleanly and when it
   fights itself.

## What this book is not

- Not a Book of Physics. There is no rigid-body engine here. The
  numbers are chosen for **feel**, not for correctness against
  Newton. A petal in this book does not obey aerodynamics; it obeys
  taste.
- Not the Book of Marionette. Marionette teaches *which* sprite is
  moving and *when*. Motion teaches *how* that sprite moves through
  the frames it was told to move through.
- Not the Book of Animation. Animation teaches craft: keyframes, the
  shape of a bounce as a drawing decision. Motion teaches the numeric
  layer underneath — the parameters an animator picks, and why a set
  of numbers reads as brick and another set as petal.

## The verbs this book uses

The general primitives, in the order they appear:

- `world/gravity!` — sets the ambient downward pull.
- `entity/velocity!` — sets a sprite's velocity vector.
- `entity/velocity` — reads it back.
- `entity/pos` and `entity/set-pos!` — position, read and write.
- `entity/squash!` — a scale deformation on impact.
- `entity/ease!` — a named easing curve applied to a motion.
- `entity/spring!` — a spring physics regime.
- `entity/lag!` — secondary motion lag against a leader.
- `entity/drift!` — air drift.
- `entity/embodiment!` — the whole regime at once, as a symbol.
- `world/step` — advance one frame.

Everything else is a combination.

## How to read it

- Read the fenced program.
- Predict where the thing ends up after `n` steps.
- Run it in the REPL.
- Change one number.
- Run it again and hear the feel change.

Prediction is the exercise; running is the check.

> **Warning**
>
> None of the programs here are safe to skip. Every one is a training
> pair. The programs on the page and the programs in the corpus are
> the same programs. If you skim, you skim past the point.

> **Tip**
>
> Read this book with the REPL open next to it. Motion is a felt
> thing. You do not learn what \"floaty\" means from a paragraph — you
> learn it from watching the same sprite fall three times with three
> different gravity numbers.

